var render = function render() {
  var _vm = this,
    _c = _vm._self._c
  return _c(
    "ContentSlotsDistributor",
    { attrs: { "slot-key": _vm.$parent.slotKey } },
    [
      _c("h2", { attrs: { id: "preface" } }, [
        _c("a", { staticClass: "header-anchor", attrs: { href: "#preface" } }, [
          _vm._v("#"),
        ]),
        _vm._v(" Preface"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _c("strong", [_vm._v("Since")]),
        _vm._v(
          " the full development of the great apostasy foretold by\nProphets and Apostles, numerous attempts at reformation have\nbeen made. Three full centuries, carrying with them the destinies\nof countless millions, have passed into eternity since the Lutheran\neffort to dethrone the Man of Sin. During this period many great\nand wonderful changes have taken place in the political, literary,\nmoral, and religious conditions of society. That the nations\ncomposing the western half of the Roman empire have already\nbeen greatly benefited by that effort, scientifically, politically, and\nmorally, no person acquainted with either political or ecclesiastical\nhistory can reasonably doubt. Time, that great arbiter of human\nactions, that great revealer of secrets, has long decided that all the\nreformers of the Papacy have been public benefactors. And thus\nthe Protestant Reformation is proved to have been one of the most\nsplendid eras in the history of the world, and must long be\nregarded by the philosopher and the philanthropist as one of the\nmost gracious interpositions in behalf of the whole human race."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "We Americans owe out national privileges and our civil liberties to\nthe Protestant reformers. They achieved not only an imperishable\nfame for themselves, but a rich legacy for their posterity. When we\ncontrast the present state of these United States with Spanish\nAmerica, and the condition of the English nation with that of\nSpain, Portugal, and Italy, we begin to appreciate how much we\nare indebted to the intelligence, faith, and courage of Martin Luther\nand his heroic associates in that glorious reformation."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "He restored the Bible to the world A. D. 1534, and boldly defended\nits claims against the impious and arrogant pretensions of the\nhaughty and tyrannical See of Rome. But, unfortunately, at his\ndeath there was no Joshua to lead the people, who rallied under the\nbanners of the Bible, out of the wilderness in which Luther died.\nHis tenets were soon converted into a new state religion, and the\nspirit of reformation which he excited and inspired was soon\nquenched by the broils and feuds of the Protestant princes and the\ncollisions of rival political interests, both on the continent and in\nthe islands of Europe."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "While Protestant hatred to the Roman Pontiff and the Papacy\ncontinued to increase, a secret lust in the bosoms of Protestants for\necclesiastical power and patronage worked in the members of the\nProtestant Popes, who gradually assimilated the new church to the\nold. Creeds and manuals, synods and councils, soon shackled the\nminds of men, and the spirit of reformation gradually forsook the\nProtestant church, or was supplanted by the spirit of the world."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Calvin renewed the speculative theology of Saint Augustine, and\nGeneva in a few years became the Alexandria of modern Europe.\nThe power of religion was soon merged in debates about forms and\nceremonies, in speculative strifes of opinion, and in fierce debates\nabout the political and religious right of burning heretics. Still,\nhowever, in all these collisions much light was elicited; and had it\nnot been for these extremes, it is problematical whether the wound\ninflicted upon the "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("Man of Sin")]),
        _vm._v(
          " would have been as incurable as it\nhas since proved itself to be."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Reformation, however, became the order of the day; and this,\nassuredly, was a great matter, however it may have been managed!\nIt was a revolution, and revolutions seldom move backward. The\nexample that Luther set was of more value than all the\nachievements of Charles V. or the literary and moral labors of his\ndistinguished contemporary, the erudite Erasmus."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          'It is curious to observe how extremes begot extremes in every step\nof the reformation cause, to the dawn of the present century. The\npenances, works of faith and of supererogation, of the Roman\nchurch, drove Luther and Calvin to the ultraism of "faith alone."'
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          'After the Protestants had debated their own principles with one\nanother till they lost all brotherly affection, and would as soon\nhave "communed in the sacrament" with the Catholics as with one\nanother; speculative abstracts of Christian Platonism, the sublime\nmysteries of Egyptian theology, became alternately the bond of\nunion and the apple of discord, among the fathers and friends of\nthe reformation.'
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v("The "),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("five")]),
        _vm._v(
          " great dogmas of the Geneva reformer were carried to\nAmsterdam, and generated in the mind of James Arminius in 1591\nfive opposite opinions; and these at the synod of Dort, in 1618,\nformed a new party of Remonstrants."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Into Britain, with whose history we are more immediately\nconcerned, Lutheranism, Calvinism, and Arminianism were soon\nimported; and, like all raw materials there introduced, were\nimmediately manufactured anew. They were all exotics, but easily\nacclimated, and soon flourished in Britain more luxuriantly than in\ntheir native soil. But the beggarly elements of opinions, forms, and\nceremonies to which they gave rise, caused the "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v('"Spirit alone"')]),
        _vm._v(
          " to\ngerminate in the mind of George Fox, in little more than half a\ncentury after the introduction of the Leyden theology."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          'In Lord Chatham\'s days, the Episcopal church, as his Lordship\ndeclares, was a singular compound — "A Popish liturgy, Calvinistic\narticles, and an Arminian clergy." But every few years caused a\nnew dissension and reformation, until the kirk of Scotland and the\nchurch of England have been compelled to respect, in some good\ndegree, the rights of conscience, even in dissenters themselves.'
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Abroad it was no better. The Saxon reformer had his friends; John\nof Picardy, lived in the grateful remembrance of the Geneva\nfamily; and James of Amsterdam, speculated in a very liberal style\namongst all the Remonstrants at home and abroad. In Sweden,\nHolland, Germany, England, Scotland, the debate varied not\nessentially: the Pope against the Protestants — the Lutherans against\nthe Calvinists — the Calvinists against the Arminians — the Bishops\nagainst the Presbyters — and the Presbyterians among themselves;\nuntil, by the potency of metaphysics and politics, they are now\nfrittered down to various parties."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          'While philosophy, mysticism, and politics drove the parties to\nevery question into antipodal extremes; while justification by\nmetaphysical faith alone; while the forms and ceremonies of all\nsects begat the "Spirit alone" in the mind of George Fox, while the\nCalvinian five points generated the Arminian five points; and\nwhile the Westminster Creed, though unsubscribed by its makers,\nbegot a hundred others — not until within the present generation did\nany sect or party in Christendom unite and build upon the Bible\nalone.'
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Since that time, the first effort known to us to abandon the whole\ncontroversy about creeds and reformations, and to "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("restore")]),
        _vm._v(
          "\nprimitive Christianity, or to build alone upon the Apostles and\nProphets, Jesus Christ himself the chief corner, has been made."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Tired of new creeds and new parties in religion, and of the\nnumerous abortive efforts to reform the reformation; convinced\nfrom the Holy Scriptures, from observation and experience, that\nthe union of the disciples of Christ is essential to the conversion of\nthe world, and that the correction and improvement of no creed, or\npartisan establishment in Christendom, could ever become the\nbasis of such a union, communion, and co-operation, as would\nrestore peace to a church militant against itself, or triumph to the\ncommon salvation; a few individuals, about the commencement of\nthe present century, began to reflect upon the ways and means to\nrestore primitive Christianity."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "This led to a careful, most conscientious, and prayerful\nexamination of the grounds and reasons of the present state of\nthings in all the Protestant sects. On examination of the history of\nall the platforms and constitutions of all these sects, it appeared\nevident as mathematical demonstration itself, that neither the\nAugsburg articles of faith and opinion, nor the Westminster, nor\nthe Wesleyan, nor those of any state creed or dissenting\nestablishment, could ever improve the condition of things, restore\nunion to the church, peace to the world, or success to the gospel of\nChrist."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "As the Bible was said and constantly affirmed to be the religion of\nProtestants, it was for some time a mysterious problem why the\nBible alone, confessed and acknowledged, should work no happier\nresults than the strifes, divisions, and retaliatory excommunications\nof rival Protestant sects. It appeared, however, in this case, after a\nmore intimate acquaintance with the details of the inner temple of\nsectarian Christianity, as in many similar cases, that it is not the\nacknowledgment of a good rule, but the walking by it, that secures\nthe happiness of society. The Bible in the lips, and the creed of the"
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "head and in the heart, will not save the church from strife,\nemulation, and schism. There is no moral, ecclesiastical, or\npolitical good, by simply acknowledging it in word. It must be\nobeyed."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "In our ecclesiastical pilgrimage we have occasionally met with\nsome vehement declaimers against human written creeds, and\npleaders for the Bible alone, who were all the while preaching up\nthe opinions of "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("saint")]),
        _vm._v(" Arius or "),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("saint")]),
        _vm._v(
          " Athanasius. Their sentiments,\nlanguage, style, and general views of the gospel were as human as\nauricular confession, extreme unction, or purgatorial purification."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          'The Bible alone is the Bible only, in word and deed, in profession\nand practice; and this alone can reform the world and save the\nchurch. Judging others we once judged ourselves, there are not a\nfew who are advocating the Bible alone, and preaching their own\nopinions. Before we applied the Bible alone to our views, or\nbrought our views and religious practice to the Bible, we plead the\nold theme, — "The Bible alone is the religion of Protestants." But we\nfound it an arduous task, and one of twenty years\' labor, to correct\nour diction and purify our speech according to the Bible alone; and\neven yet we have not wholly practically repudiated the language of\nAshdod. We only profess to work and walk by the rules which will\ninevitably issue in a pure speech, and in right conceptions of that\npure, and holy, and celestial thing called Christianity — in faith, in\nsentiment, and in practice.'
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "A deep and an abiding impression that the power, the consolations,\nand joys — the holiness and happiness — of Christ's religion were lost\nin the forms and ceremonies, in the speculations and conjectures,\nin the feuds and bickerings of sects and schisms, originated a\nproject many years ago for uniting the sects, or rather the\n"
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("Christians")]),
        _vm._v(
          " in all the sects, upon a clear and scriptural bond of\nunion — upon having a "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v('"thus saith the Lord,"')]),
        _vm._v(
          ' either in express terms,\nor in approved precedent, "for every article of faith, and item of\nreligious practice." This was offered in the year 1809, in the\n"Declaration and Address" of the Washington Association,\nPennsylvania. It was first tendered to the parties that confessed the\nWestminster creed; but equally submitted to the Protestants of'
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "every name, making faith in Christ and obedience to him the only\ntest of Christian character, and the only bond of church union,\ncommunion, and co-operation. It was indeed approved by all; but\nadopted and practiced by none, except the few, or part of the few,\nwho made the overture."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "None of us who either got up or sustained that project, was then\naware of what havoc that said principle, if faithfully applied, would\nhave made of our views and practices on various favorite points.\nWhen we take a close retrospective view of the last thirty years,\n(for we have a pretty distinct recollection of our travel's history for\nthat period,) and of the workings of that principle in heart and life,\nwith which we commenced our public career in the work of the\nLord; we know not how to express our astonishment better than in\nthe following parable: —"
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "A citizen of the West had a very promising young vineyard on a\nfruitful hill. He had no practical knowledge in the cultivation of the\ngrape; but had read much and largely upon the dressing, pruning,\nand managing of the vine. He built himself a wine-vat, and\nprepared all the implements for the vintage. But he lacked practical\nskill in using the pruning knife. His vines flourished exceedingly,\nand stretched forth their tendrils on every side; but he had no\nvintage."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "A vine-dresser from Oporto one day presented himself as he was\nmusing upon his disappointments. He was celebrated in his\nprofession, and the most skillful in all the affairs of the vineyard.\nThe owner of the vineyard having employed him to dress and keep\nhis vineyard, set out on a long journey for a few weeks. On his\nreturn and visit to his farm, he walked out one day to his vineyard;\nwhen, to his amazement, he saw the ground literally covered with\nprunings of his vines. The vine-dresser had very skillfully and\nfreely used the pruning hook, and had left little more than the roots\nand naked stems of the vines standing by the frames."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "'My vineyard is ruined! My hopes blighted! I am undone! I am\nruined!' exclaimed the unhappy husbandman. 'Unhappy wretch!\nyou have deceived me; you have robbed me of the labors of five\nyears, and blasted, in one single moon, all my bright hopes for"
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "years to come!' The vine-dresser stood appalled; but soon as the\ntempest subsided, ventured to say, — 'Master, I will serve you five\nyears for nothing, if we gather not more grapes and have not a\nbetter vineyard this year, than you have gathered in all the years\nsince you planted these vines.' The proprietor of the vintage\nwithdrew, saying, — 'It is impossible! It is impossible!' and visited it\nnot again till invited by his vine-dresser about the middle of\nautumn; when, to his still greater astonishment, and much more to\nhis gratification, he found incomparably more grapes than hitherto\ngathered from his vines, and of a much more delicious quality."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "So in the case before us, the application of the principle already\nstated trimmed us so naked, that we strongly inclined to suspect its\nfallacy, and had well-nigh abandoned it as a deceitful speculation.\nTime, however, the great teacher, and Experience, that great critic,\nhave fully assured us that the principle is a salutary one, and that\nalthough we seemingly lose much by its application, our loss\nconsists only of barren opinions, fruitless speculations, and useless\ntraditions, that only cumber the ground and check the word, so that\nit is in a good measure unfruitful."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "We flatter ourselves that the principles are now clearly and fully\ndeveloped by the united efforts of a few devoted and ardent minds,\nwho set out determined to sacrifice everything to truth, and follow\nher wherever she might lead the way: I say, the principles on\nwhich the church of Jesus Christ — all believers in Jesus as the\nMessiah — can be united with honor to themselves, and with\nblessings to the world; on which the gospel and its ordinances can\nbe restored in all their primitive simplicity, excellency, and power,\nand the church shine as a lamp that burneth to the conviction and\nsalvation of the world: — I say, the principles by which these things\ncan be done are now developed, as well as the principles\nthemselves, which together constitute "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("the original gospel and order\nof things")]),
        _vm._v(" established by the Apostles."),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "The object of this volume is to place before the community in a\nplain, definite, and perspicuous style, the capital principles which\nhave been elicited, argued out, developed, and sustained in a\ncontroversy of "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("twenty-five years")]),
        _vm._v(", by the tongues and pens of those"),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "who rallied under the banners of the Bible alone. The principle\nwhich was inscribed upon our banners when we withdrew from the\nranks of the sects, was, "
        ),
        _c("em", [
          _vm._v(
            "'Faith in Jesus as the true Messiah, and\nobedience to him as our Lawgiver and King, the "
          ),
          _c("em", [_vm._v("only test")]),
          _vm._v(" of\nChristian character, and the "),
          _c("em", [_vm._v("only bond")]),
          _vm._v(
            " of Christian union,\ncommunion, and co-operation, irrespective of all creeds, opinions,\ncommandments, and traditions of men.'"
          ),
        ]),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "This cause, like every other, was first plead by the tongue;\nafterwards by the pen and the press. The history of its progress\ncorresponds with the history of every other religious revolution, in\nthis respect — that different points, at different times, almost\nexclusively engrossed the attention of its pleaders. We began with\nthe "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("outposts")]),
        _vm._v(
          " and vanguard of the opposition. Soon as we found\nourselves in the possession of one post our artillery was turned\nagainst another; and as fast as the smoke of the enemy receded we\nadvanced upon his lines."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          'The first piece that was written on the subject of the great position,\nappeared from the pen of Thomas Campbell, Senior, in the year 1809. An association was formed that year for the dissemination of\nthe principles of reformation; and the piece alluded to was styled\n"The Declaration and Address of the Christian Association of\nWashington, Pennsylvania."'
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          'The constitutional principle of this "Christian Association" and its\nobject are clearly expressed in the following resolution: — "That this\nsociety, formed for the sole purpose of promoting simple\nevangelical Christianity, shall, to the utmost of its power,\ncountenance and support such ministers, and such only, as exhibit\na manifest conformity to the '
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("Original Standard")]),
        _vm._v(
          ", in conversation\nand doctrine, in zeal and diligence; only such as reduce to practice\nthe "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("simple original")]),
        _vm._v(
          " form of Christianity, expressly exhibited upon\nthe sacred page, without attempting to inculcate anything of human\nauthority, of private opinion, or inventions of men, as having any\nplace in the constitution, faith, or worship of the Christian church;\nor anything as matter of "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("Christian faith")]),
        _vm._v(" or "),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("duty")]),
        _vm._v(", for which there\ncannot be produced a '"),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("thus saith the Lord,")]),
        _vm._v("' either in express terms\nor by approved precedent.\""),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "The ground occupied in this resolution afforded ample documents\nof debate. Every inch of it was debated, argued, canvassed, for\nseveral years, in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Ohio. On this bottom\nwe put to sea, with scarcely hands enough to man the ship. We had\nhead winds and rough seas for the first seven years. A history of\nwhich would be both curious and interesting."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "But to contradistinguish this plea and effort from some others\nalmost contemporaneous with it, we would emphatically remark,\nthat, while the remonstrants warred against human creeds,\nevidently because those creeds warred against their own private\nopinions and favorite dogmas, which they wished to substitute for\nthose creeds, — this enterprise, so far as it was hostile to those\ncreeds, warred against them, not because of their hostility to any\nprivate or favorite opinions which were desired to be substituted\nfor them; but because those human institutions supplanted the\nBible, made the word of God of non-effect, were fatal to the\nintelligence, union, purity, holiness, and happiness of the disciples\nof Christ, and hostile to the salvation of the world."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Unitarians, for example, have warred against human creeds,\nbecause those creeds taught Trinitarianism. Arminians, too, have\nbeen hostile to creeds, because those creeds supported Calvinism.\nIt has, indeed, been alleged that all schismatics, good and bad,\nsince the days of John Wickliffe, and long before, have opposed\ncreeds of human invention because those creeds opposed them. But\nso far as their controversy resembles them in its opposition to\ncreeds, it is to be distinguished from them in this all-essential\nattribute, viz. — that our "
        ),
        _c("em", [
          _vm._v(
            "opposition to creeds arose from a\nconviction, that whether the opinions in them were true or false,\nthey were hostile to the union, peace, harmony, purity, and joy of\nChristians; and adverse to the conversion of the world to Jesus\nChrist."
          ),
        ]),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v("Next to our personal salvation, two objects constituted the\n"),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("summum bonum")]),
        _vm._v(
          ", the supreme good, worthy of the sacrifice of all\ntemporalities. The first was the union, peace, purity, and\nharmonious co-operation of Christians — guided by an\nunderstanding enlightened by the Holy Scriptures; the other, the"
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "conversion of sinners to God. Our predilections and antipathies on\nall religious questions arose from, and were controlled by, those\nall-absorbing interests. From these commenced our campaign\nagainst creeds. We had not at first, and we have not now, a favorite\nopinion or speculation, which we would offer as a substitute for\nany human creed or constitution in Christendom."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "We were not, indeed, at first apprised of the havoc which our\n"
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("principles")]),
        _vm._v(
          " would make upon our opinions. We soon, however,\nfound our principles and opinions at war on some points; and the\nquestion immediately arose, "
        ),
        _c("em", [
          _vm._v(
            "Whether shall we sacrifice our\nprinciples to our opinions, or our opinions to our principles?"
          ),
        ]),
        _vm._v(
          " We\nneed not say that we were compelled to the latter; judging that our\nprinciples were better than our opinions. Hence, since we put to\nsea on board this bottom, we have been compelled to throw\noverboard some opinions once as dear to us as they now are to\nthose who never thought of the difference between principle and\nopinion."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Some of these opinions — (as the most delicate and tender buds are\nsoonest blighted by the frost) — immediately withered, and died\nunder the first application of our principles. Infant baptism and\ninfant sprinkling, with all infantile imbecility, immediately expired\nin our minds, soon as the "
        ),
        _c("em", [_vm._v("Bible")]),
        _vm._v(
          " alone was made the only measure\nand standard of faith and duty. This foundation of the Paidobaptist\ntemple being instantly destroyed, the whole edifice leaning upon it\nbecame a heaps of ruins. We explored the ruins with great\nassiduity, and collected from them all the materials that could be\nworked into the Christian temple; but the piles of rubbish that\nremained were immense."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "Other topics became the theme of discussion; and as the public\nmind became more intelligent and candid, the great principles of\nthe Law and Gospel, the Patriarchal, the Jewish, and Christian\nInstitutions were gradually unfolded. To the development of these,\nother publications in 1816 and 1820 greatly contributed; and so\nfully explored were ancient and modern Christianity, that, in 1823,\nthe design was formed of commencing a periodical and"
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "establishing a press to contend for the original faith and order, in\nopposition to all the corruptions of fifteen centuries."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "As we are not writing a history of this struggle from its\ncommencement till the present time, but simply informing the\nreader that the principles stated in the following pages have been\nmaturely considered, and have passed through a long, complicated,\nand vigorous oppositions, — we shall hasten to the object of this\nbook, which is to lay before the reader a miniature view of the\nprinciples already noticed."
        ),
      ]),
      _vm._v(" "),
      _c("p", [
        _vm._v(
          "To say nothing of the periodicals which have already been\ncommenced, and which have been for some time our\nfellow-laborers, in this all-important work, besides our debtors of\n1820, 1823, and 1829, four editions of the new version of the New\nTestament, with prefaces, various tables, notes, criticisms, etc.;\nthere have been issued from our press "
